<TEXT>
the national conference of catholic bishops is 
moving toward a showdown vote on whether to reject a draft vatican 
document questioning the theological authority of such conferences 
the bishops softened the wording of their proposed reply to the 
vatican document on monday but pressed toward a scheduled wednesday 
vote without changing their underlying judgment the draft is not 
suitable 
despite frequent public compliments from both sides relations 
have often been uneasy between the vatican and bishops conferences 
particularly those such as the americans which have seemed to be 
growing in prestige in recent years 
pope john paul ii has publicly supported many of the us 
conferences efforts including national pastoral letters that 
stirred controversy outside the church for their criticism of reagan 
administration policies on nuclear arms and the us economy 
however there also has been criticism from high vatican 
officials who have asked for whom the bishops were speaking in 
commenting on matters of doctrine and on what authority 
also on monday acceding to a vatican request the bishops 
postponed a vote on another controversial item but did so only 
grudgingly and with rare public complaints about the way church 
leaders in rome had handled the situation 
while the bishops gave ground they took pains to say they were 
not knuckling under to vatican pressure 
we have not bowed obsequiously to rome in an untoward 
fashion said archbishop oscar lipscomb of mobile ala objecting 
to a reporters suggestion that that was what had happened 
about 300 us roman catholic cardinals archbishops and bishops 
had been scheduled to vote today on new guidelines for settling 
disputes between theologians and bishops but a letter from the 
vaticans congregation for the doctrine of the faith complained that 
the guidelines would make the theologians and bishops equals in the 
settlement process 
bishop raymond lessard of savannah ga chairman of the bishops 
committee on doctrine said he felt all that was sufficiently 
addressed in the guidelines document however he added that it 
seemed wise to postpone action until the bishops june meeting 
several bishops complained about the timing of the vaticans 
complaint including cardinal joseph bernardin of chicago who said 
the intervention might be perceived as confrontational or as 
belittling the episcopal conference which i know is not intended 
cardinal john oconnor of new york said the vatican agency was 
understaffed a possible explanation for the lastminute nature of 
the objection however archbishop john may of st louis president 
of the us bishops conference said the vatican had had the 
proposal for more than a year 
as for the draft vatican document on bishops conferences a 
number of us bishops apparently had been stung by news stories 
quoting in advance from the proposed rejection notice 
the new version distributed by a committee of past conference 
presidents on monday is considerably toned down from the original 
which had used such phrases as rigid and confusing and overly 
defensive and negative to describe the vatican draft 
however it still calls for the bishops to label the vatican 
effort nonplacet so flawed that it isnt even suitable to be 
used as a basis for revision 
several bishops objected to such a label suggesting it would be 
a slap at the vatican this raised the possibility that the 
conferences objections would have to be softened further if they 
are to win the twothirds majority necessary in wednesdays vote 
in other action monday the bishops 
gave first reading to one proposal that would call for easing of 
a 1986 law and give legal standing to many more undocumented 
hispanic workers and to another resolution calling for acceleration 
of religious freedom and an end to intimidation of worshipers in the 
soviet union and other eastern bloc countries 
postponed action on a resolution calling for movement toward 
normalization of relations between the united states and vietnam 
archbishop roger mahony of los angeles said vietnameseamerican 
groups in this country were divided on the issue but he said the 
postponement was merely to give the bishops time to consider 
conditions in southeast asia in general 
heard archbishop pio laghi the vatican representative to the 
bishops as well as to the us government call for greater effort 
in keeping hispanicamericans in the church he did not publicly 
mention the simmering vaticanbishops disputes 
