<TEXT>
the energy department says it overestimated how 
much natural gas american industry has been using a mistake that 
had set off false alarms about the energy efficiency of the us 
economy 
the error arose when a new reporting form confused many of the 
companies that report gas deliveries to the departments energy 
information administration 
eias quarterly publication short term energy outlook for 
october which reached users monday said the previous quarters 
estimates of industrial natural gas consumption in the first half of 
1988 were about 8 percent too high 
the agency started checking its statistics when the july edition 
of its outlook reported a 26 percent firsthalf increase in 
industrial gas use implausibly high 
in fact the first half increase was about 6 percent to 313 
trillion cubic feet 
natural gas is a major source of energy for home heating 
electricity generation chemical manufacture and industrial process 
heat a little less than a quarter of all energy comes frm gas 
industrial gas use is about 8 percent of the total national energy 
bill 
without the exaggerated natural gas changes there would have 
been no significant change in the estimated energy efficiency in the 
economy the closely watched ratio of energy used in producing a 
dollars worth of goods and services 
environmentalists use this as a rough indicator of damage to the 
environment from economic activity policymakers watch it as an 
indication of future vulnerability to interruption of oil imports 
ken brown an eia analyst said the agency distributed new 
reporting forms to gas companies delivering gas to industrial users 
with the start of 1988 the new forms asked for physical deliveries 
of gas no matter who owned it 
the old forms required listing deliveries only of gas owned by 
the reporting company no matter who delivered it 
some companies continued to report the old way which meant some 
gas was counted twice once by the owner once by the shipper 
eia said 43 companies apparently have consistently misreported 
their monthly deliveries resulting in an overstatement of 
industrial consumption in the first six months of 1988 of 05 
trillion cubic feet 
now that the errors have been corrected the agency expects 
industrial gas use of 615 trillion cubic feet for all of 1988 only 
a 44 percent gain instead of the 19 percent increase projected in 
july on the basis of the overestimates 
the energy crises of the 1970s prompted major efficiency 
improvements everywhere in the united states for example autos 
averaged about 13 miles per gallon of gasoline in 1973 congress 
required 275 mpg by 1985 a goal since relaxed to 26 mpg 
more efficient processes have continued to be introduced in 
industry and energy efficiency gains accelerated from an average of 
12 percent per year in the 1970s to 28 percent in 19801986 
but in 1987 for the first time in 11 years efficiency failed to 
improve a stagnation many analysts attributed to the collapse in 
oil prices of 1986 
it took 19960 british thermal units or btu to produce a 
dollars worth of goods and services in 1987 measured in dollars of 
1982 buying power this was roughly the same as the 19950 btu of 
1986 
a btu is a standard unit of energy equal to the amount of heat 
needed to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree 
fahrenheit 
in july the agency forecast a 1988 ratio of 20180 btu per 
dollar or a 11 percent decline from 1987 and a 1989 ratio of 
20050 a 06 percent improvement from 1988 
the corrected october forecast predicts 19840 btu per dollar an 
improvement of 06 percent from 1987 and improvement of 13 percent 
to 19590 btu in 1989 
one analyst alan durning of the worldwatch institute an 
environmental research group said i could believe an 
improvement of 06 percent 
i would expect gains in the aggregate of about a half 
percent per year just from the technologies and how much room for 
improvement there is almost indefinitely durning said 
but at the lawrence berkeley national laboratory in berkeley 
calif analyst lee schipper said that even after the data 
corrections as far as im concerned thats no change theres a 
plateau if i were a policymaker id be worried 
