<DOCNO> AP881115-0030 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the palestine national council is a 
450member bicameral parliamentinexile with members selected from 
palestine liberation organization guerrilla factions and 
professional unions 
the council elects the plos ruling 15man executive committee 
sets out the committees policy distributes finances to the 
movements seven departments and regulates relations with 
governments and other organizations 
in short it is the palestinians supreme decisionmaking body 
the council is led by sheik abdelhamid sayeh a 78yearold 
moslem priest who was deported from the israelioccupied west bank 
after the 1967 middle east war 
the parliament is supposed to convene annually but the executive 
committee may call special sessions for internal regional or 
international developments 
another body the central council meets regularly its 70 
members who include the executive committee members oversee 
implementation of pnc resolutions 
the plo council first was formed in jerusalem in 1964 
after the 1967 war when israeli took control of the west bank and 
gaza strip 100 additional members were added to allow 
representation of the gaza area which had been under egyptian rule 
when east jerusalem was occupied the council moved to cairo 
egypt where it drafted the plo charter in 1968 
arab governments endorsed the guerrilla movement as the sole 
legitimate representative of the palestinian people in a summit 
the same year 
after egypt signed the camp david peace treaty with israel in 
1979 the council moved out of cairo since then the pnc has held 
sessions in syria jordan and algeria 
there are independent council members and those designated by plo 
factions and unions such as those representing students lawyers and 
women 
independents occupy 199 seats the rest are distributed to the 10 
unions and guerrilla factions 
council decisions also are made by majority vote 
fatah the plos largest faction which is headed by yasser 
arafat has 55 seats the largest block in the council 
about 80 percent to 85 percent of the delegates are aligned with 
arafat 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881115-0031 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
excerpts of un security council resolution 242 which was 
unanimously adopted nov 22 1967 
1 affirms that the fulfilment of charter principles requires the 
establishment of a just and lasting peace in the middle east which 
should include the application of both the following principles 
i withdrawal of israel armed forces from territories occupied 
in the recent conflict 
ii termination of all claims of states of belligerency and 
respect for and acknowledgement of the sovereignty territorial 
integrity and political independence of every state in the area and 
their right to live in peace within secure and recognized boundaries 
free from threats or acts of force 
2 affirms further the necessity 
a for guaranteeing freedom of navigation through international 
waterways in the area 
b for achieving a just settlement of the refugee problem 
c for guaranteeing the territorial inviolability and political 
independence of every state in the area through measures including 
the establishment of demilitarized zones 
3 requests the secretarygeneral to designate a special 
representative to proceed to the middle east to establish and 
maintain contacts with the states concerned in order to promote 
agreement and assist efforts to achieve a peaceful and accepted 
settlemernt in accordance with the provisions and principles in this 
resolution 
4 requests the secretarygeneral to report to the security 
council on the progress of the efforts of the special representative 
as soon as possible 
