<TEXT>
the rate of jobrelated injuries and illnesses 
increased by 5 percent last year with 351000 more injuries and 
53000 more illnesses reported the government said today 
the bureau of labor statistics said 83 of every 1000 workers 
experienced some kind of jobrelated illness or injury last year 
compared with 79 of every 1000 workers in 1985 and 1986 
meanwhile jobrelated fatalities in surveyed private businesses 
with 11 or more employees dropped from 3610 in 1986 to 3400 last 
year bls officials called the decline statistically 
insignificant 
the increase in injury and illness rates was the first since 1984 
a total of 5843100 workers were injured on the job last year 
compared with 5492000 in 1986 the bureau said 
nearly half of the injuries were so severe that employees lost a 
full day or more of work and the number of work days lost totaled 
488 million compared with 454 million work days lost to injuries 
in 1986 
some 190000 workers suffered new illnesses for the first time 
most of them involving noiserelated hearing losses skin diseases 
and repetitive motion ailments such as carpal tunnel syndrome 
prevalent in the meatpacking industry 
that is a 28 percent increase over the 136900 new cases of 
jobrelated illnesses reported in 1986 
the bureau said chronic and longterm latent cases that are often 
difficult to recognize or relate to the workplace are included in 
the illness statistics but are clearly understated 
labor statistics commissioner janet l norwood said the increase 
in the job injury and illness rates may be due to better 
recordkeeping due to new government guidelines and intensive efforts 
to improve the statistics 
the national academy of sciences last year questioned validity of 
the governments job health and safety data because of severe 
underreporting by employers to avoid workmens compensation claims 
or government inspections 
an academy panel said the actual number of jobrelated fatalities 
could be as much as triple those reported by the bureau 
the occupational safety and health administration has placed a 
new emphasis on accurate records levying hundreds of fines some of 
them in the millions of dollars against employers for not reporting 
jobrelated injuries or illnesses 
of the 3400 reported onthejob fatalities last year twothirds 
occurred in the construction manufacturing transportation or 
public utility industries as in previous years the single biggest 
cause was traffic accidents accounting for about onethird of the 
deaths the government said 
