<TEXT>
china opened an international exhibit of its 
arsenal tuesday complete with scale models and videos of the weapons 
in action 
the china precision machinery import and export corp one of the 
countrys largest arms manufacturers said it was putting six new 
missiles on the market during the fourday asian defense technology 
exposition or asiandex 88 
they included several mediumrange coastal defense missiles 
intended to replace the silkworm which vice president shen rengui 
said used outdated technology and was being phased out 
the silkworm became chinas most famous missile when iran used 
one in october 1987 to attack a kuwaiti oil tanker flying the 
american flag china denied selling silkworms to iran and said it 
did not know where iran bought them 
but western experts said the new missiles and other weapons shown 
at asiandex already were being promoted to potential buyers and 
that the show contained no surprises 
the exhibit demonstrated chinas determination to increase its 
arms sales despite criticism from the united states and other 
western countries that chinese sales to primarily third world 
countries are destabilizing 
china does not release figures on its arms sales but the us 
government estimates china sold sold about 2 billion in weapons 
abroad in 1987 it is the fourthlargest weapons seller to the third 
world after the soviet union united states and france 
china began taking part in international arms shows in 1984 and 
held the first show of its own asiandex 86 two years ago 
nearly 100 foreign companies also had booths at the exhibition 
including the us companies boeing and lockheed britains marconi 
group hungarys technika foreign trading co and chiles cardoen 
arms manufacturers from france west germany italy the netherlands 
and other countries also were represented 
one western manufacturer said his company attended not in hopes 
of making an immediate sale to china but simply to keep up contacts 
with the chinese military weve talked with them and they sent a 
team to tour our plant at one point but nothing he said 
a western source noted china has been uninterested in importing 
large quantities of weapons 
what they want is joint ventures so they can learn the 
technology and reverseengineer and make it themselves he said 
speaking on condition of anonymity 
many of chinas current weapons were derived in this way from 
1950s soviet models in recent years china has entered into 
agreements with western companies to use their advanced technology 
to upgrade its obsolete arsenal 
aeritalia of italy supplied avionics technology for chinas new 
a5m fighter plane which recently had a successful test flight 
us and british companies also have cooperated in updating chinese 
tanks and planes 
chinas strategy has been to use arms exports to subsidize 
improvements in its domestic arsenal that it could not otherwise 
afford its biggest market has been the middle east where it has 
sold to both iran and iraq during their 8yearold border war 
</TEXT>
