<TEXT>
a chance remark at a parisian dinner party two 
years ago led to the discovery of a longlost collection of rare 
islamic art that will go on public display sunday at the smithsonian 
institutions arthur m sackler gallery 
the collection assembled by henri vever a turnofthecentury 
jeweler and art collector in paris is perhaps the most important 
purchase in the history of the smithsonian institution says 
smithsonian secretary robert mcc adams 
the 500 items in vevers collection of richly detailed paintings 
manuscripts calligraphies and bookbindings from ancient persia 
india and other major artistic centers of the near east were bought 
for 7 million 
smithsonian officials say their real worth is much much more 
but that the collection is priceless in scope and quality 
drawn from the vever collection are 150 items that will be 
displayed at the sackler many of them for the first time anywhere 
from sunday through april 30 in a show titled a jewelers eye 
islamic arts of the book from the vever collection 
an hourlong smithsonian world television special on vever 
and his collection will be broadcast on public tv stations next 
march 
vevers collection includes almost all of the great classical 
persian texts several important arabic works and previously unknown 
manuscripts and paintings from major artistic centers of the near 
east and india 
the art works some dating to the 11th century reflect the 
reverence for the written word in medieval islam stemming from the 
holy scriptures of the prophet muhammad known as the koran the 
ruling elite built libraries of lavishly illuminated books and 
manuscripts as symbols of their cultural sophistication 
vevers collection includes brilliant paintings in which the 
pigments were ground from minerals precious stones and metals an 
irresistible attraction to the jeweler and his contemporary henri 
cartier 
smithsonian officials say the only comparable collection in the 
world is housed at the chester beatty library in dublin ireland 
vevers collection disappeared in the late 1930s during the 
german occupation of france vever himself died in 1942 and the 
whereabouts of his collection remained a mystery for nearly half a 
century 
then during a small dinner party in paris in november 1984 
laure lowry of williamstown mass found herself seated next to 
francois mautin a wealthy elderly sportsman and naturalized 
american who casually disclosed a momentous secret 
mautin said he was vevers grandson and had inherited a major 
collection of islamic art which was shipped intact from france to 
new york city after world war ii for safekeeping there it remained 
stored in a vault known only to mautin 
mrs lowry telephoned the news to her son glenn d lowry 
curator of near eastern art at the freer gallery of art and the 
yetunbuilt sackler gallery lowry was dumbfounded he and milo c 
beach now acting director of the sackler raced to paris and won 
mautins commitment to sell the collection to the smithsonian 
lowry and beach were the first scholars to see the collection by 
then moved to london in 50 years among the wellpreserved items 
hidden in trunks and stacked against walls was a surprise 39 full 
manuscripts previously unknown to scholars except for a handful that 
were exhibited in london in 1931 
the 7 million purchase was financed by various smithsonian trust 
and acquisition funds and private donors including the late dr 
arthur m sackler chief benefactor of the underground museum that 
opened in september 1987 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

