<TEXT>
a new electronic toll system that will read a 
special automobile tag may help motorists whiz by toll booths under 
an experiment planned by two new yorkarea authorities 
the number of times a vehicle goes through the toll would be 
recorded by computer and a monthly bill charged to a credit card 
the new system called automatic vehicle identification or avi 
uses a radio frequency beam transmitter mounted in each lane that 
will read a unique serial number up to 20 digits from a tag mounted 
on each vehicle 
a similar system now being experimented with in dallas is working 
well officials there said 
the triborough bridge and tunnel authority hopes to experiment 
with the new system at the verrazanonarrows bridge a span between 
staten island and brooklyn that carries about 58 million vehicles a 
year beginning early next year martin gottlieb the tbtas 
project manager for avi said monday 
however the experiment which could cost up to 14 million 
must first be approved by the metropolitan transportation authority 
the tbtas parent agency 
if approved tags would be fitted on vehicles belonging to some 
trucking companies as well as vehicles belonging to tbta employees 
and transit authority buses that use the bridge according to tbta 
spokeswoman catherine sweeney 
the port authority of new york and new jersey which is 
experimenting with a similar system for buses at the lincoln tunnel 
plans to use the same trucking companies for its experiment at the 
goethals bridge according to armando arrastia a port authority 
spokesman the goethals bridge connects staten island and new jersey 
in addition he said the new jersey turnpike the new jersey 
state highway authority and the new york state thruway authority are 
all committed to using the same avi system 
the decision to use the verrazanonarrows and goethals bridges 
was made because a lot of the traffic would be the same sweeney 
said many longdistance truckers cross staten island to avoid 
manhattan 
the speed of proccessing at the toll booths is the main 
advantage of the system gottlieb said it will reduce the need 
to handle cash tickets and tokens 
the new york and new jersey transportation officials are 
optimistic about the system because of good results from a similar 
experiment in dallas by the texas turnpike authority that started 
last summer 
its coming along very well said harry kabler a spokesman 
for the authority 
the dallas experiment is being conducted on the north dallas 
tollway and is currently limited to employees of amtech of texas 
one of two companies that has developed the automated system the 
tollway is a heavily traveled 20milelong highway between downtown 
dallas and its northern suburbs 
