<TEXT>
potato seedlings treated with a genetically 
modified bacteria designed to protect plants from frost damage 
suffered onethird as much damage as unprotected plants a 
researcher reported tuesday 
two years of smallscale field tests proved the procedure to be 
safe and effective according to steven lindow associate professor 
of plant pathology at the university of california at berkeleys 
college of natural resources 
lindow was scheduled to report his findings tuesday at the annual 
meeting of the american phytopathological society in san diego 
similar research by other scientists has shown that genetically 
modified bacteria can protect strawberry plants from frost 
the minor genetic modification was designed to counter the effect 
of common bacteria whose structure triggers frost formation on 
plants at temperatures just below freezing lindow and an associate 
genetically modified a strain of the bacteria so it lacked the 
frostpromoting gene but was otherwise unchanged 
the modified bacteria was applied to potato seedlings before 
naturally occurring bacteria could gain hold monitoring showed that 
the modified bacteria could not be detected beyond the experiments 
93foot buffer zone 
lindows field tests were delayed for almost four years because 
of safety concerns about outdoor experiments using genetically 
engineered organisms 
but lindow said the genetically altered bacteria wont thrive 
outside of the treated area because other bacteria are established 
there 
established frostfighting methods such as sprinklers and wind 
machines can be more effective but they work in a narrower 
temperature range and are more expensive to administer than the 
bacteria strategy lindow said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

