<TEXT>
a judge tuesday revoked the bail of 
eight defendants as he prepared to deliver the verdict in a 
threeyear trial of the leaders of south africas biggest 
antiapartheid group 
the 19 black defendants who belong to the banned united 
democratic front have pleaded innocent to charges of treason 
terrorism murder and subversion related to an allegation that they 
sought to promote violence in order to make south africa 
ungovernable 
supreme court justice kees van dijkhorst began delivering a 
summary of the trial and is expected to announce the verdicts in two 
or three days 
sixteen of the 19 black defendants had been granted bail during 
the trial van dijkhorst did not explain why he revoked the bail of 
only eight defendants the three most prominent defendants senior 
leaders of the united democratic front have been denied bail and 
have spent 40 months in jail they are popo molefe 36 who was the 
united democratic fronts national secretary terror lekota 40 who 
was its publicity secretary and moses chikane 40 who was 
secretary of its transvaal province branch 
the united democratic front south africas largest opposition 
group was founded in 1983 and includes more than 600 antiapartheid 
groups with about 2 million members it was banned in february 
the charges against the 19 arise from violence and mob killings 
in black townships south of johannesburg in september 1984 that were 
the start of two years of nationwide unrest in which more than 2500 
people were killed 
treason and murder carry a maximum penalty of death 
van dijkhorst who has presided over the nonjury trial since it 
began in june 1985 has sole responsibility for the verdict and 
sentencing he was initially assisted by two lay experts but one 
was dismissed because he had signed a petition supported by the 
united democratic front opposing constitutional changes that 
excluded blacks from parliament 
van dijkhorst said tuesday the defendants were not being 
prosecuted for their political views he said it was possible to 
commit treason even if one believed a new government would serve the 
interests of a majority of the people 
under south africas policy of apartheid the 26 million blacks 
have no voice in national affairs which are controlled by the 5 
million whites 
</TEXT>
