<DOCNO> AP881115-0173 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a governmentsponsored panel of diverging 
interests on tuesday recommended a major overhaul of wetlands 
protection with states assuming responsibility for a national goal 
of creating more wetlands than are being destroyed 
the national wetlands policy forum convened by the conservation 
foundation at the request of the environmental protection agency 
said the proposed goal of ending the conversion of wetlands to other 
uses did not mean every single parcel of marshy ground would have to 
be preserved but enough wetlands should be created or restored to 
outweigh the losses 
the federal government has hundreds of wetlands rules but 
there is no guiding principle no overriding goal said new jersey 
gov thomas h kean who served as chairman of the forum the 
result is confusion equal to rush hour on the beltway 
the 20member forum embraced representatives of builders 
industry environmental groups state and local governments and 
federal agencies its recommendations were presented as a consensus 
package and kean and others said the group would oppose attempts to 
pick out particular measures from the more than 100 recommendations 
to support or oppose 
about half the 200 million acres of marshes and bogs fens 
swamps and other wetlands that were present in the lower 48 states 
when european settlement began have been converted to other uses 
farms housing developments shopping centers airports and 
everything else that humans do 
in recent decades though environmental benefits of wetlands 
have been recognized increasingly storage of flood water cleansing 
of pollution protection of wildlife spawning and nursing of 60 
percent to 90 percent of the nations commercial fish catch 
recharging groundwater and controlling erosion 
a major study in the 1970s estimated that losses over the two 
previous decades had proceeded at 400000 acres half the size of 
rhode island to 500000 acres per year no one knows if that still 
holds true epa uses 350000 acres and a recent congressional study 
used 275000 acres 
among major recommendations of the forum 
a national agricultural wetlands reserve which would pay farmers 
to transfer land or easements to wetlands preservation trusts these 
trusts would operate somewhat like the nature conservancy and other 
private groups to hold reserved land the reserve should aim to 
protect 5 million existing acres and restore half as much the forum 
said 
each state should enact wetlands protection plans which if 
approved by epa would qualify the state to take over many though 
not all of epas wetlands protection jobs only michigan has taken 
over epa wetland regulation tasks so far 
states with approved programs might be able to issue regional 
general permits which would allow the conversion of a limited amount 
of ecologically low value wetland areas in exchange for full 
compensatory mitigation 
federal activities would have to be consistent with approved 
state plans just as they now must be in states with approved 
coastal zone management plans 
regulatory authorities should take any necessary action 
including amending existing regulations to prevent the willful 
alteration of wetland characteristics to circumvent regulatory 
jurisdictions 
make the definitions of wetlands uniform some 50 different 
definitions of wetlands are in use throughout the federal government 
a major effort to identify public lands where wetlands could be 
restored with priority attention to the louisiana coasts 
extremely high wetlands losses from erosion and subsidence 
largely as a result of government flood control and other water 
resource projects 
the report noted the fact that the protection of wetlands 
makes good economic as well as environmental sense for society but 
not necessarily for the individual owning them is central to much of 
the conflict over wetlands protection policies and a conservative 
advocacy group singled out that point as one weakness 
property owners have a right to develop their property said 
robin l rivett of the pacific legal foundation of sacramento 
calif adding that there is no mention in this report of the 
fifth amendment problem 
he referred to court rulings that some land use regulations can 
be so burdensome as to amount to a taking of property for public 
use that requires compensation to the owner under the constitutions 
fifth amendment 
tom hookano of the foundation said the group believes major 
wetlands need protection but he said the report does not go beyond 
recommendations of the regulatory task force chaired by vice 
president george bush in 1982 
its irresponsible to recommend a program without a price 
tag he said arguing that the agricultural wetlands reserve could 
cost billions of dollars 
the national audubon society and the national wildlife 
federation whose leaders took part in the study endorsed the 
report but one environmental group that did not participate said it 
had serious concerns about delegating authority to the states 
because state and local governments were more vulnerable to pressure 
from development interests than the federal government 
dave malakoff of friends of the earth said were suspicious of 
state control were not sure the states have the resources to 
regulate in this area 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

