<TEXT>
negotiators reached tentative agreement tuesday 
on a plan that will bring namibian independence from south africa in 
early 1989 and a cuban troop withdrawal from angola over a 27month 
period us officials said 
the agreement was worked out during five days of negotiations in 
geneva involving officials from south africa cuba and angola it is 
subject to final approval by their respective governments 
us officials insisting on anonymity said current plans call 
for the formal agreement to be signed in early december the accord 
was mediated by us assistant secretary of state chester crocker 
the plan calls for implementation starting in february of a 
un security council resolution designed to end south africas 
73year rule over namibia africas last colony 
under the plan elections for namibias first independent 
government will be held in august and the new regime will take 
office in early 1990 the officials said 
a second part of the agreement envisions the withdrawal of 
twothirds of the more than 50000 cuban troops in angola during the 
oneyear period ending in december 1989 
the agreement also calls for the gradual redeployment of 
remaining cuban troops northward away from the namibian border and 
from the stronghold of anticommunist angolan rebels backed by the 
united states 
in geneva no details were disclosed but south africas chief 
negotiator neil van heerden said all parties have agreed to 
take a document home to their governments 
he said the document would be the basis for a final agreement 
if the parties accept it 
cuba first sent troops to angola in 1975 to help the fledgling 
independent government newly freed from portuguese colonial rule 
fend off military incursions from south africa which was concerned 
about communist penetration of the region 
with the exception of a residual force all the cubans will be 
back home by early 1991 under the timetable agreed to in geneva 
left unanswered is the fate of the usbacked rebel movement 
known by its portuguese initials unita 
south africa has been the principal supplier of the unita forces 
for years ferrying equipment across the namibian border to the 
rebel stronghold in southeast angola 
but with south africa apparently intending on removing its forces 
from namibia that country will no longer be able to continue its 
resupply operation because of logistical problems 
presidentelect george bush has said us support for unita will 
continue but american officials have indicated that the south 
african resupply role cannot be duplicated 
on the other hand the officials said that cuba has played an 
indispensable role in supporting the angolan army and that the 
removal of the cuban troops will shift the military balance in 
unitas favor 
crocker has sought to bring an end to angolas internal conflict 
by calling for national reconciliation negotiations between angolas 
marxist government and the unita rebels 
but the angolan government has rejected negotiations with unita 
calling instead on the rebels to lay down their arms and join in a 
national reconstruction effort 
</TEXT>
