<TEXT>
brazilians voted tuesday in 
municipal elections seen as popularity test for president jose 
sarneys government exit polls showed the government trailing 
badly a television network said 
at stake were mayoralties and city legislatures in 4307 cities 
and towns in latin americas biggest country 
sarney has been widely blamed for the countrys economic 
stagnation inflation approaching 2000 percent a year and a 40 
percent drop in workers buying power 
exit polls showed the government party leading in just six of 
brazils 24 state capitals according to tv globo the nations 
largest private network in 1985 mayoral and city council elections 
the same party took 17 major cities 
preelection polls showed sarneys brazilian democratic movement 
party which in 1986 swept elections for state governors state 
assemblies and congress will be fortunate if it wins even three 
mayorships in brazils 14 largest cities 
more than 75 million registered voters were to choose from 12 
million candidates belonging to 29 parties ranging from two 
communist groups to supporters of the former military regime 
lines at polling places were four city blocks long in many cities 
some results were expected late tuesday but officials said final 
results probably would not be announced until sunday 
voting is mandatory and brazilians who dont vote face trouble 
getting a passport obtaining a government loan or a civil service 
job 
sarney the first civilian president since a 21year military 
regime ended in 1985 called the elections a step toward 
democracy 
dont think democracy is easy to be a democrat its 
necessary to renounce violence and convince by ideas and choose by 
the ballot the president told a nationwide television audience 
monday night 
but recent polls showed voter apathy and distrust of politicians 
were high in rio de janeiro many brazilians took advantage of the 
national holiday and the warm weather to crowd the citys famous 
beaches leaving voting for later 
in recent weeks a campaign begun by a satirical newspaper to 
elect a chimpanzee in the rio zoo as mayor has gained national 
attention as a sign of brazilians lack of confidence in politicians 
in general 
public service announcements on radio and television urged 
brazilians not to throw away their votes by casting blank ballots or 
voting for nonsense candidates 
federal troops were stationed in 15 states and 271 municipalities 
to keep order 
police arrested some campaign workers for violating a law 
prohibiting lastminute campaigning within 300 feet of polling 
stations the workers were trying to hand out sample ballots with 
their candidates name written in 
sarney voted in his northern home state of maranhao then 
returned to the capital of brasilia 
sarney a 58yearold politician and poet gained office as the 
running mate of tancredo neves who was chosen in a 
militarycontrolled electoral college vote neves died shortly 
before taking office 
the elections are viewed as an important indicator of party 
popularity as brazil prepares for presidential elections in late 
1989 the first such election in 29 years 
