<TEXT>
having plowed the financial harvest of 1987 
into this years crop cotton farmers of the texas high plains are 
expecting to reap bountiful results again this fall 
with the harvest in full swing crop observers are forecasting a 
total yield of about 27 million bales from 3 million acres for the 
25county area that stretches from amarillo in the panhandle of the 
state south to midland in west texas 
thats slightly below last years bumper crop of 27 million 
bales from 27 million acres which marked the secondhighest 
peracre yield on record behind 1965 when slightly more than one 
bale an acre was harvested 
texas leads all us states in cotton production and the high 
plains area alone produces more than any state except texas 
the 1987 crop eased financial burdens on many farmers allowing 
them to pay off loans and buy new equipment unlike years past 
during this growing season they had some money to spend on better 
fertilizer more irrigation and pest control 
people were in a better position to invest a little more in 
this crop said cotton agronomist james supak of the texas 
agricultural extension service weve gone through some pretty 
tough ones people are still working largely on borrowed money but 
it was a little easier to finance this crop because of the better 
production last year 
the weather also played a big part in what should be backtoback 
crop successes warm and dry conditions in october improved yield 
prospects by about 10 percent over earlier forecasts say crop 
observers as a result the cotton bolls or seed pods matured 
before a freeze could kill the plants 
area growers could have been tending an even better crop had more 
rainfall soaked fields during the summer 
this could have been an exceptional crop perhaps a record 
crop had we caught a rain in august supak said the dryland 
cotton went through a pretty severe drought stress that will put a 
cap on production 
crops in most areas were spared from severe hail damage which 
all but devastated the 1986 crop but drought conditions will cut 
into the harvest in some areas of west texas 
michael gruber an extension agent in one west texas county 
estimated that farmers in his area would bring in only about 8000 
bales over 55000 acres compared with 22000 bales last year 
scant rainfall and boll weevil infestation in the area where 
dryland farming predominates doomed crops early on 
we didnt have any rain through july august or september 
said gruber the drier it got the worse the bugs got us and 
before we knew it we didnt have any cotton 
still state agriculture officials project that texas cotton 
crop will be the fourthlargest in 10 years down about 7 percent 
from 1987 
while cotton experts say the quality of this years high plains 
cotton has been good so far market prices have edged lower 
it appears that the demand for cotton is somewhat weaker now 
than it was at this time last year especially the export demand 
said don ethridge of texas tech universitys agricultural economics 
department i also see that there is some weakness in the domestic 
demand for cotton and that is certainly affecting the market 
price 
ethridge attributed the weakness in demand to a sluggish economy 
but the high plains economy should pick up as a result of 
consecutive bountiful harvests said lj richardson jr president 
of first national bank in brownfield texas 
since agriculture is the base of the economy in brownfield 
it just has a tremendous impact on our local economy and the 
financial institutions he said 
the influx of deposits from last years crop boosted first 
national to a record 94 million in assets 
we expect that when we get this crop in well reach the 100 
million mark he said 
despite the hopeful outlook weatherrelated misfortunes could 
still befall the cotton before its out of the field later this 
month said supak 
what would tend to hurt us would be weather systems that would 
come in here with ice and snow and moisture he said cotton is 
very vulnerable at this stage to weathering and will lose its color 
if exposed to moisture 
