<TEXT>
if the makers of ruffies are accurate in their 
view of america making gains in the garbage bag business is a 
matter of appealing to the nations conscience 
polytech inc of bloomington minn is launching a line of 
degradable plastic trash bags with hopes that us households will 
pay a little extra for ruffies knowing they have the potential to 
turn to dust 
weve gotten just a tremendous response said robert 
doernbach chairman and chief executive officer of polytech a 
company founded in 1958 by flamboyant philanthropist percy ross who 
sold out in 1969 its going to be interesting to see if people 
will go out and buy those products 
its not the first time degradable garbage bags have been 
marketed but doernbach says ruffies is the first nationally 
advertised brand to make the move 
on their part its smart marketing said frank rolfes a 
securities analyst for dain bosworth inc of minneapolis i think 
people like to do the environmentally right thing 
by adding photosensitive material to the plastic compound the 
bags break down when they are exposed to ultraviolet light from the 
sun once the chain reaction begins the bags eventually are reduced 
to a fine powder the company says the bags will completely degrade 
in about three months in direct sunlight the company says 
but theres a catch doernbach said bags must be exposed to the 
sun a minimum of about seven days for the breakdown process to begin 
give or take a few days depending on seasons and the bags 
distance from the equator 
given the dark nature of landfills most bags wont degrade 
with the way they are normally used rolfes said 
still degradable bags are helpful in the fight against litter 
and even the darkest landfill cant stop the degrading process of a 
bag once it starts doernbach said 
the technology will add about a dime to the retail cost of a 
package of 30 tall kitchen containersized bags which vary in price 
from 199 to 269 depending on where they are sold 
hopefully theres some profit there but its not a wildly 
profitable thing doernbach said 
ruffies with about 400 employees in bloomington denver and 
battleboro nc controls about 8 percent of the total us 
consumer trash bag market while its two other national competitors 
glad and hefty each has about a 30 percent share doernbach said 
polytech posted 718 million in revenues in 1987 but earned 
just 472000 rolfes said the degradable bags could give polytech 
a small sales edge in some locations but not enough to make a 
nightandday difference because the product could easily be 
duplicated by competitors if it skyrockets 
rick tanner product manager for glad trash bags in danbury 
conn said hes neither surprised nor worried about the change in 
ruffies 
this is not a hot button with consumers tanner said 
polytech is responding to special interests 
tanner and allen gray a spokesman for mobil corp which makes 
hefty bags said its a waste of time and resources to make garbage 
bags degradable 
the degrading process takes far far too long to create extra 
space in landfills gray said the money is much better spent on 
real solutions to the problems 
although plastics only account for an estimated 72 percent of 
the countrys solid waste as measured by weight many experts 
believe plastics pose a much greater problem than the figures reveal 
because they are so light 
about 96 million tons of plastic were discarded in the united 
states in 1984 and the volume is expected to increase 98 percent to 
155 tons by 1990 
recycling garbage incineration and reducing the stream of solid 
waste are environmental causes more worthy of corporate concern 
gray said 
its a matter of taking care of the volume that we generate and 
reducing that volume he said 
still hefty will be keeping an eye on ruffies sales to see what 
consumers want 
mobils position has been if the market demands that the bags 
be made biodegradable well do it gray said 
