<DOCNO> AP881115-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
behind his ramshackle wooden counter 
luiz ferreira costa sells anything from toilet paper and cigarettes 
to cooking oil and rice literally for the price of gold 
his prices are calculated in grams of the yellow metal 
onetenth of a gram worth about 2 for a dozen eggs or a half a 
gram for 2 pounds of coffee 
costas customers are part of an estimated 1 million prospectors 
who have invaded brazils vast amazon rain forest to tap its rich 
gold deposits 
fortunes are made but the gold rush also is creating widespread 
violence smuggling tax evasion health problems environmental 
pollution and even the disturbance of primitive indians 
the gold dust which costa carefully weighs on his scale comes 
from the bed of the madeira river that flows past teotonio a small 
prospectors camp 25 miles from porto velho capital of the western 
jungle state of rondonia about 2000 miles northwest of rio de 
janeiro 
this is my way of digging for gold said costa a 
58yearold potbellied toothless man who claimed he was too old 
to put up with the roughandtumble life led by most gold diggers 
according to jose altino machado a director of the gold 
prospectors federation there are close to 3000 golddigging sites 
spread out over the 2 million square miles of the socalled legal 
amazon comprised of the states of amapa para roraima maranhao 
goias acre rondonia mato grosso and amazonas 
since the late 1970s close to 600000 newcomers have swelled 
the ranks of the 400000 professional prospectors who have been 
working in the region for years and if you include spinoff services 
such as food equipment transportation and prostitution the number 
of people living off the gold rush jumps to 7 million machado 
said 
most prospectors were poor peasants fleeing brazils 
droughtridden northeast but over the past few years businessmen 
doctors and lawyers have also become gold diggers they make more in 
six months than in five years behind their desks machado said 
he said a prospector extracts on the average at least 50 grams of 
gold worth about 1000 a month 
most work for wellestablished entrepreneurs who take 70 percent 
of the production in exchange for equipment transportation 
medicine and food very few get rich machado said 
but fortunes are made in the jungle about 5000 prospectors have 
earned at least 1 million and some 200 are worth more than 5 
million he said 
most of the gold from the amazon never finds its way into the 
national economy buyers who purchase the gold directly from the 
prospectors hoard it or acquire dollars as a hedge against 
inflation or smuggle it out of the country to evade income and 
mineral extraction taxes 
marcos antonio maron an official of the mines and energy 
ministrys national mineral production department said lack of 
funds and manpower make it almost impossible to police the vast 
expanse of land on which the gold digging sites are located 
in an interview maron said that of the estimated 100 tons of 
gold produced in brazil in 1987 only 35 tons were registered with 
the government for 1988 he estimated a real production of 110 
tons versus a registered production of no more than 55 tons 
ministry figures show that between 1977 and 1986 almost 23 
billion of gold was detoured from the economy 
in terms of real production brazil ranks sixth among the worlds 
largest gold producers coming after south africa the soviet union 
the united states canada and australia 
maron said brazil has known reserves of 1000 tons of gold he 
said geological studies have not been made to pinpoint gold reserves 
in the amazons but all told i would estimate brazil has a 
potential of producing about 30000 tons of gold 
a lot of gold is found inside indian territory this has led to 
several conflicts especially with the yanomami tribe in the 
northern state of roraima near the frontier with venezuela maron 
said 
police and army troops occasionally evict prospectors from indian 
territory but they keep coming back he said 
machado admitted prospectors work near indian territory but 
never invade it it is the indians who enter prospectors camps and 
dig for gold and they are always welcomed 
amazon gold comes from huge openpit mines or is blasted from the 
earth with high pressure water hoses pumped from riverbeds or 
simply panned by solitary prospectors 
the most serious environmental hazard posed is the use of 
mercury a metallic chemical element used to join gold dust 
particles 
the mercury is burned off the gold emitting a highly toxic gas 
that enters the atmosphere and can be inhaled by the prospector the 
toxins can cause nervous disorders and genetic deformations in 
offspring 
maron said 180 tons of mercury enter the amazons ecosystem every 
year affecting the regions flora and fauna and poisoning the 
rivers 
along a 370mile stretch of the madeira river some 5000 dredges 
daily suck up huge amounts of gravel which yield more than 4 tons 
of gold a year 
near the teotonio prospectors camp paulo oliveira employs 16 men 
on his two dredges which operate 24 hours a day seventythree feet 
below hoses acting like giant vacuum cleaners pump up about 6 tons 
of gravel per hour 
on hundreds of small barges competing with dredges for space 
divers plunge into the dark muddy waters handcarrying smaller 
versions of the suction hoses 
joaquim lins 23 dives twice a day air pumped through a tube 
by an engine on the barge allows him to remain underwater for two 
hours at a time 
lins profession is a dangerous one he runs the risk of bursting 
his lungs by getting his air tube tangled with those of other divers 
or with the dredges hoses divers are also known to cut their 
rivals air supplies 
scores die this way each year lins said as he prepared to 
dive 
but its not only divers who die for gold each day at least four 
people are shot dead in teotonio mainly because they didnt obey 
our unwritten code of ethics said oliveira 
here its live and let live and work and let work anyone who 
doesnt follow this rule dies 
machado oliveira and other prospectors interviewed denied 
reports that drug traffickers from neighboring bolivia and colombia 
cross frontiers to exchange cocaine for gold 
but we have information of traffickers buying gold with dollars 
as part of their moneylaundering process machado said 
more than 1000 gold feverstricken prospectors enter the amazon 
each year hoping to strike it rich and according to machado very 
few will leave the jungle because once you come down with the fever 
you never want to recover 
</TEXT>
