the united states will need just about as much 
imported steel next year as this year even if an economic recession 
reduces overall steel consumption a leading steel importer said 
the requirement for foreign steel will be a central issue in 
washington dc as debate heightens over the extent to which 
presidentelect george bush should renew steel import quotas due to 
expire next sept 30 
domestic producers cannot sustain production much above 80 
percent of rated capacity and exports are expected to grow said 
fred lamesch president of the importer tradearbed inc of new york 
and past president of the american institute for imported steel 
for this year domestic shipments are expected to reach 83 
million tons imports 21 million tons and exports 2 million tons 
leaving total us consumption of 102 million tons he said monday 
night in new york during an address to members of the association 
for steel distributors eastern region 
lets assume steel consumption drops five million tons to 97 
million tons next year if as widely forecast exports rise by two 
million tons we would still need 20 million tons of imported steel 
in this market and for specific products and regions dependence on 
imported steel is much greater lamesch said 
lamesch said domestic producers can be expected among other 
things to begin filing unfair trade cases as early as spring as 
they lobby for an extension of the trade restraint agreements 
domestic producers prefer a situation in which the sum of their 
own capacity plus imports does not surpass a level that will 
threaten future price stability the importer said in practice 
that translates into an effort first to keep closed domestic 
capacity from being reopened and second to extend and expand 
restraint agreements 
