<TEXT>
small businesses are feeling better about the 
economic outlook these days with an increasing number thinking 
about adding more jobs building new plants and maintaining 
relatively high inventory levels 
but dont expect to see too much in the way of salary increases 
over the next few months according to the latest quarterly survey 
by a leading trade group 
the national federation of independent business whose 500000 
member firms employ about half the countrys nonfarm work force 
reports that its smallbusiness optimism index rose to 1029 in 
october from 1005 in july 
the seasonally adjusted index which assumes conditions that 
existed in 1978 equal 100 reached a high of 1087 in january 1984 
and a low of 811 in april 1980 earlier this year it had been 
slippping 
firms had become decidedly less optimistic about future 
economic growth during the year explained william c dunkelberg 
dean of temple universitys business school and originator of the 
survey 
but the declines of early 1988 were reversed in october 
returning to levels that prevailed in 1986 and early 1987 
the data compiled in the survey of 2084 small responding 
businesses includes predictions on expected business conditions the 
climate for expansion earnings job openings and hiring plans and 
plans for capital outlays 
dunkelberg said the overall sentiment of responding firms could 
be summed up this way there is still no sign that there is 
substantial weakness in the economy or that a recession is likely to 
start anytime before mid1989 
strong earnings are supporting strong plans to hire and spend 
on inventories and capital projects 
among details of the report 
eighteen percent of the firms plan to increase total employment 
in the next three months while 11 percent plan reductions the 
percentage of firms with job openings set a record for the current 
expansion rising to 25 percent and surpassing the previous high of 
23 percent last january 
the employment rate should continue to fall under such 
pressure the report said 
twentynine percent reported raising prices in the third 
quarter unchanged from the previous period while 8 percent reduced 
prices down two percentage points from july plans to lift prices 
fell one percentage point from july levels to 25 percent of all 
firms 
although not large there is a clear upward drift in the 
percent of firms planning to raise prices but nonfood 
inflation should fall off somewhat in the fourth quarter the 
report said 
planned capital outlays rose to an alltime seasonally adjusted 
high of 35 percent fiftyfive percent reported outlays in the last 
six months although the spending rate is still nine percentage 
points below the high level set in 1979 
plans to add to inventories were unchanged from july levels but 
remained strong in comparison to the past four years seventeen 
percent planned to add to inventories while 17 percent planned to 
reduce 
accumulations have been heavy among retail and wholesale firms 
perhaps in anticipation of the christmas selling season the 
report said 
the percentage of firms borrowing on a regular basis rose to 38 
percent from a recordlow 35 percent of all firms apparently 
profits and cash flow are sufficient to meet he capital needs of 
most small firms 
twentysix percent reported increases in employee wages in the 
third quarter of 1988 up one percentage point from the previous 
period plans to increase wages rose three percentage points to 21 
percent of firms 
with job openings at expansionhigh levels there is still 
little evidence that compensation is responsiding in any substantive 
way to labor market tightness the report said 
