<TEXT>
just days after initiating an industry move to 
drop discounts aimed at business travelers continental airlines 
announced a restructured maxsaver program tuesday that is 
expected to boost most remaining cutrate fares 
continental said maxsaver fares which are used by most vacation 
travelers would be based on the length of a flight under the new 
formula 
competition on individual routes not mileage had determined the 
fares in the past 
it was not immediately clear whether other big carriers would 
follow continentals move but the airline has been the pacesetter 
on fares in recent years 
the airline planned to notify travel agents about the new fares 
tuesday night and wednesday spokesman ned walker said in a 
telephone interview from continentals headquarters in houston he 
said the new maxsaver fares would take effect next wednesday 
you will see some maxsavers going up and some maxsavers going 
down walker said we are returning air fares to a more rational 
level 
he said fares for longer flights generally would be raised while 
those for shorter hauls would mostly be reduced 
some travel agents told about the changes said they appeared to 
have the effect of raising roughly twothirds of continentals 
maxsaver fares and cutting the remaining third or so 
theyre going to raise it to the level that it should have been 
in the first place said jack bloch the owner of jbs world 
travel in new york 
maxsaver tickets must be purchased seven to 14 days in advance 
and require an overnight stay 
air fare structures have become geographically out of whack 
as a result of airlines frequently matching each others fare 
increases in recent months said robert decker an airline analyst 
for duff amp phelps inc in chicago 
the changes come amid plans by texas air corp subsidiary 
continental and other big us airlines to eliminate another 
category of discount air fares the junk fares available four 
to seven days before a flight and used mainly by business travelers 
in a move initiated by continental and followed by several major 
carriers the junk fares were slated to be eliminated on tuesday 
but the airlines decided to extend the deadline by a week because of 
confusion over the change 
only about 10 percent to 20 percent of all airline passengers use 
the lastminute junk fares according to some analysts estimates 
the popular maxsaver fares by contrast are used by most 
vacation travelers 
more than 90 percent of air travelers use some form of discount 
fare be it lastminute or advance purchase according to the air 
transport association an industry trade group based in washington 
the discounts generally arent available for flights during 
holidays like thanksgiving and christmas 
some examples of changes in continentals oneway maxsaver fares 
are 
between newark nj and houston current offpeak fare 129 
current peak fare 159 new offpeak 139 new peak unchanged 
between boston and dallas current offpeak 149 current peak 
169 new offpeak and peak both unchanged 
