<TEXT>
members of a union coalition 
representing 9200 workers at walt disney world voted overwhelmingly 
tuesday to accept a new threeyear contract ending a strike threat 
against the giant tourist attraction 
harvey totzke president of the sixunion service trades council 
reported union members voted 1059677 to approve the agreement 
which provided for immediate pay raises of 35 cents to 50 cents 
asked about two previous rejections of similar offers and 
repeated calls by some union members for a strike totzke said i 
think they finally took a realistic look at the offer i can say it 
now it was a fair offer we got all we could get 
bill ward disney vice president for labor relations said im 
obviously very happy about it we felt that we had a good contract 
rejection by twothirds of the voters would have authorized labor 
leaders to call a strike 
among the workers represented by the service trades council are 
ride operators sandwich makers bus drivers stockroom workers 
hotel housekeepers and clerks animal handlers monorail pilots and 
the people who portray mickey mouse donald duck goofy and other 
characters 
the company has said it was prepared for normal operations in the 
event of a strike disney officials planned to fill park operating 
jobs from among the 13000plus nonunion employees and from among 
management workers who chose not to observe a strike call and any 
people hired after a strike call 
the balloting was the second within four days 
an election last friday was nullified by union bosses who 
discovered some workers voted more than once angry employees 
rejected two earlier contract proposals contending they did not 
offer enough money for pay raises 
the new contract provides pay raises of 50 cents an hour to 
workers now at top scale who earn from 680 to 970 an hour and 
raises of 35 cents an hour for workers below top scale who now make 
485 to 920 an hour 
in april 1990 workers at top scale would get pay hikes of 45 
cents an hour while those below top scale would receive 30 cents an 
hour 
workers rejected an earlier package offering wage increases of 5 
percent in the first year and 4 percent in each of the contracts 
final two years plus other benefits 
dissatisfaction by many union members dates back to 1985 when 
the unions agreed to a twoyear wage freeze and took onetime 
bonuses instead two weeks later the company announced record 
revenue and profit for its 1985 fiscal year union members said 
the service trades council is composed of the service employees 
international union the hotel employees amp restaurant employees 
union the united food and commercial workers the transportation 
and communication union the international brotherhood of teamsters 
and the international alliance of theatrical stage employees 
</TEXT>
