<TEXT>
most of the insurance companies that quit 
selling and renewing policies after last weeks voter approval of a 
ratecutting initiative have returned to the market according to an 
industry survey released tuesday 
but far fewer companies are offering homeowners and business 
liability policies according to the survey by the independent 
insurance agents and brokers of california 
the survey which gauged the market as of monday suggested that 
fears of mass insurer defections from the california market after 
last weeks passage of proposition 103 a ballot initiative that 
would deeply cut insurance rates were exaggerated 
numerous companies suspended policy sales and renewals after the 
initiative passed last tuesday but many have returned to the market 
since the state supreme court acting on an industry lawsuit put 
the measure on hold pending a trial 
as of monday the brokers group found companies making up 81 
percent of the california market were selling new auto insurance 
policies renewals were being offered by companies representing 94 
percent of the market 
for reasons the group has yet to determine the figures were far 
lower for homeowners and business policies 
insurers accounting for 75 percent of the market for homeowners 
policies were selling new policies while renewals were available 
from companies making up 83 percent of the market 
new commercial insurance policies were available from companies 
holding just 54 percent of that market and renewals were available 
in 66 percent of the market 
the figures are based on direct communication with 75 insurance 
carriers that hold more than 90 percent of the market and were 
valid as of monday said joseph annotti spokesman for the agents 
group 
while the high courts stay has returned stability to the market 
the longterm health of the industry and the availability of 
insurance to consumers depends on the outcome of the lawsuit 
annotti said he repeated frequent industry warnings that most 
insurers would incur unacceptable losses if proposition 103 were 
upheld 
the measure backed by consumer crusader ralph nader was 
approved by voters who rejected four other competing initiatives 
proposed by industry or trial lawyers groups 
proposition 103s principal effect would be to roll rates for 
nearly all types of insurance back to november 1987 levels and then 
impose an additional 20 percent cut 
</TEXT>
